diers and world leaders, ordinary people make vital contributions to a nation's military engagements. Alvah broadens the scope of the history of the Cold War by analyzing how ideas about gender, family, race, and culture shaped the U.S. military presence abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmericanszForeign countriesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold War. 0aFamilies of military personnelzUnited States. 0aMilitary spouseszUnited States. 4aAlvah. 4aCold. 4aUS. 4aabout. 4aabroad. 4aanalyzing. 4abroadens. 4aculture. 4afamily. 4agender. 4ahistory. 4aideas. 4amilitary. 4apresence. 4arace. 4ascope. 4ashaped. 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814705315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814705315.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK